The station was opened by the German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation, in August 1908.
Germany, the "late future" of conquests, wanted to achieve its ambitions to occupy the Middle East by using this railway from Damascus through Baghdad to what is now Saudi Arabia.
German conquest efforts collapsed during World War I.
His railroad lines were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and Arab partisans.
The relative isolation from surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The British colonial army withdrew from Egypt and drove the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
Hyderpasha station was no better.
In 1917, a machine gun train exploded and destroyed the beautifully designed roof of the building.
Turkish sources say there was a sabotage.
It has since slowly fallen into disrepair and has gone well beyond history.
However, today, as a railway gateway to Anatolia and the entire eastern region, Turkey serves as an expanding diplomatic horizon, at least in a symbolic sense.
The ruling Justice and Development Party, the AKP, has developed a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from surrounding regions caused by the frozen borders of the Cold War has disappeared.
The new policy is marked by commitment.
It is noteworthy that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian groups Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq, Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
I wanted to measure the parameters of the new foreign policy, so I took a night train to Ankara, the capital of Turkey, to visit one of the leading foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish parliamentarian Suat Kiniklioglut.
The next morning, after about 10:30 a.m. of darkness, which set the tone for the then famous documentary about the Old World, "The Night Mail", I arrived in the Turkish capital, the new city intended to be a symbol of the new secular state that turned its back on the Ottoman past.
However, the AKP, which has well-known Islamic roots, represents a paradigm shift in the Turkish consensus.
This has caused some suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
I took a taxi to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern building made of stone and steel, specifically designed for this purpose -- located in a developing suburb, between half-finished shopping malls and coffee shops.
Suat Kiniklioglu would have been a right-wing politician in any other European country.
He was wearing a suit, a tie, and I'm sure he even had a Blackberry.
"The party's foreign policy objective is to help Turkey reintegrate into its immediate environment.
The Cold War has upset the order", he said.
From the backdrop of Turkey's isolation.
Today, he had to turn east and west at the same time.
She couldn't choose between the two.
It had to be opened in both directions.
"But is it possible that sooner or later you will be forced to make a choice?" I asked.
"Turkey never wanted to be left out of the way".
He then stressed what almost everyone I spoke to here almost automatically repeated: Turkey's relations with not only the Middle East but also with the countries surrounding the Caucasus and the Black Sea are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as Turkey is to itself.
It's like they want to convey the message that, in a literal sense, all of Europe, along with Turkey, can get to Asia and the Middle East on those eastbound railways.
When I was at Hydarpasha station again, after another, mostly awake night, I thought of Herr Ritter and Herr Conura, the two German gentlemen who 100 years ago watched the reconstruction of this ornate building.
How surprised they would be to learn that Europe's Middle Eastern ambitions are now largely in Turkey's hands.
And as I waited for the ferry to take me back through the Bosporus at the port, I remembered that at the time Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
