The "Meat Car" Avoiding a Collision
To develop accident prevention technologies, Nissan was inspired by nature, precisely the world of bees, for its new invention.
The Japanese company has designed a robot that mimics the behavior of bees to avoid accidents.
It could be a Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive or BR23C that's the first step in developing collision prevention technologies.
Engineers at Nissan Motor Co.'s Advanced Technology Center, in collaboration with the renowned Tokyo University's Advanced Science and Technology Research Center, built this little robot in Japan.
The BR23C is a further extension of the Nissan four-seater safety-cover as defined by Kazuhhiro Doi, Director of Technology PR and R&D.
The robot will enhance the collision-avoidance capabilities of the company's products.
During flight, each bee forms its own oval-shaped personal space, which is very similar to the Nissan safety coat.
But much more important is the bee's complex eye, which allows it to see at more than 300 degrees in all directions, and therefore the bee can fly uninterrupted in its own personal space.
To mimic the function of the complex eye, engineers designed a laser rangefinder.
The instrument shall identify obstacles, calculate their distance and send a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which shall be immediately converted into a collision avoidance operation, within a distance of up to 2 metres from the BR23C at a distance of 180 degrees.
"Once the obstacle is detected, the little robot immediately changes direction by following the movements of the uterus, moving the wheels at smaller or larger angles to avoid collision.
The main difference between the system and the instruments currently available is that in this case the avoidance maneuver is completely automatic.
Otherwise, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobility Laboratory and project chief engineer.
Unlike the bees, the avoiding maneuver cannot be directed up or down, nor transverse, but can only move in two dimensions and only in the direction of the reversal of the wheels, i.e. not in infinite directions and ways, as in the case of bees.
That's why Nissan used a rotation function in the robot to avoid collisions, in addition to acceleration and slowing down.
"This device only needs to process and respond to the data every few seconds.
It doesn't need data storage or intuitive logic based on previous maneuvers, so it can work without interruption with just a few dozen KB of memory.
This may sound surprising, but it's not really a gigabyte, but we're not even talking about megabyte-sized memory.
This is the first step towards developing an instantaneous collision prevention technology that Nissan estimates could be introduced into series production cars within 10 years.
The robot is powered by lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and more durable than the lithium-ion version.
In the future, the integration of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system may be an additional possibility to help the car reach its destination by avoiding road obstacles.
