Statement by Rafael Correa on Monday, Quito
Reconstruction of the republic in the spirit of 21st century socialism.
This is the joint project of Hugo Chávez of Venezuela, Evo Morales of Bolivia and Rafael Corre of Ecuador.
Following the example of his fellow presidents and friends, Correa expressed his views on the new constitution on Sunday.
It succeeded in its mission, with 64% of voters voting yes to the referendum according to the official results, which were 80% of the votes cast.
That 28% of the population voted yes, 7% of the votes were invalid, while 0.7% were rejected by voters.
The draft constitution required 50% + 1 vote.
Two polls at the polling stations on Sunday and a counting by a civil organization both showed a huge surge in yes votes of 63% and 70% respectively.
Rafael Correa, by the way, was already talking about his constitutional bill winning on the night of Sunday to Monday.
"The Constitution has won a decisive victory", he declared, thanking the Ecuadorians at his governor's residence in Guayaquil, about 300 miles (280 km) southwest of Quito.
As is well known, Rafael Correia was congratulated by Chávez, Morales and Chilean President Michelle Bachelet.
The report by the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission said the vote was conducted in a calm atmosphere, with a 444-point text summarizing the principles of "new socialism" defended by the president.
The proposed constitution places state power at the service of the economy, retaining the state's right to "planning development" for a country that primarily relies on oil production by foreign companies and foreign exchange sent by migrants.
The Correa constitution, which was elected in 2006, also strengthens the power of the head of state, who can serve a maximum of two consecutive terms and is entitled to dissolve the parliament.
Correa has already announced that he wants to take this opportunity and will run again for the presidency in February 2009.
The constitution also includes free health care and education, and the president has already begun implementing it in a country of 13.9 million people and half of the population living below the poverty line.
Finally, the Constitution prohibits foreign troops from entering the country, which could end the Quito-Washington agreement to use the Ecuadorian facility as the base for U.S. drug control.
