In the United States, life and health insurers often refuse to take out insurance contracts with applicants based on the information they have about people buying medicines.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
'There is a data protection programme which binds the use of prescription data to the consent of the person concerned in any case.
It must be in independent hands, or the fox will be the chicken", says Richard Dicket, a program developer who tracks prescriptions for drugs.
Insurance companies shall make the insurance premium and the accident insurance premium dependent on the health status of the applicant and shall not insure the risk if they consider it too high.
In the past, the person was sent for a medical examination and the contract was only concluded with the knowledge of the results.
Dick invented a much cheaper procedure ten years ago: Using a customer ID, he can easily obtain from pharmacies what medicines he's bought in the last year and a half, and the program itself can infer what disease he's suffering from and what his medical condition is.
For example, if you take a regular high dose of a cholesterol lowerer, it indicates that you have practically untreatable high blood fat levels, which immediately puts you in a higher risk category.
There are several versions of the programme in circulation, some of which also set a risk multiplier, so the insurer has little to do outside the paperwork, although minor difficulties arise.
The disadvantages include that some medicines can be used for multiple purposes, such as certain compounds can be used to treat migraines or heat waves, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter is a significant risk-increasing factor for business insurers, while the former is not.
Separate companies have been set up to collect and process the data, and they ask for the patient's consent before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies.
