Some companies have recently been processing laboratory results and linking them to drug use data to provide an even more accurate picture of patients' health.
More and more companies have access to the data, and controlling usage is becoming increasingly difficult.
There's a separate health data protection law, but it only applies to healthcare providers and insurers.
Congress is currently considering legislation that would give authorities control over data-processing firms.
Dick Richard realizes that this is not enough: he has therefore developed his program, which would involve the express consent of the data subject.
